segments.text: And we're in the office of Bill Yunkin here in Bryan.
Now we're going to stop and hope that the machine is working.
A while ago, didn't get the date, March 24, in the office of Bill Yunkin.
And we're going to chat about what it was like to be a student at A&M back a few years.
Why did you attend A&M?
Well, my basic impetus for attending A&M came from, as I guess it does for most folks, from influences in your life, from people in your home town area.
None of my family had ever gone to college.
My father, World War II, at that age, would be in college and came back.
I was, I guess, what you call the first of the baby boomers.
My dad got out of the service in 1946, and nine months later, in January 1947, there I am.
So they didn't have that educational influence on me, although they would have liked to have gone to college.
It really came about while I was growing up in the,
a school system there in Gilmer where I was born.
We had a lot of people who were community leaders in the town that were A&M graduates.
Gilmer is an Aggie town.
And the reason it's an Aggie town kind of goes back to one particular person.
Everybody talks about 12th Man Superior, E. King Gill coming out of the stands, et cetera, et cetera.
Well, on the field that day was a young man who was playing center and middle linebacker for the Aggies.
His name was Henry McCullough.
What's Henry McCullough?
M-C-C-U-L-L-O-U-G-H. And Mr. Henry, as he was known to generations of kids growing up in Gilmer, after he graduated from A&M, came home to college school and coached Bob.
And he has gone through about three generations now that are direct influences of Mr. Henry's recruitment process.
When I was in high school, he'd already retired.
He'd been principal, superintendent, etc.
He was just teaching chemistry and analytical geometry and some of the other math courses.
I had him for that.
What he would do is he would talk about his days staying home and playing for DX Bible and all those memories and things.
And it got you interested in the school.
And he was a person of tremendous respect in our community.
The leading citizens of the community,
other than their parents, because one person they truly respected, admired, and revered would be Mr. Henry.
And so when Mr. Henry ever came up to you and put his arm around you and said, Bill, you ever thought about going to A&M?
You knew you'd kind of pass muster in his eyes for the quality of person that he thought should be going to his university.
And there were other people there, too, in the community that were former students.
that had an influence.
And one of the other aspects too is I did get an opportunity to come down here early on in my life, like my early teenage years, because I was involved in 4-H and FFA.
I was a farm boy.
I was from a farming family.
And I lived in Gilmore.
I lived 10 miles from Gilmore.
That's what actually it was.
And because of that interest,
and help with my county agent, Mr. John Henry, who is retired and lives here in Collin Stochendam.
Mr. Grover Bishop, who's my ag teacher, is deceased now.
But those men bringing me down here for judging contests and leadership camp and things of this nature.
I got to see the campus and stuff like that.
And through that interest,
It led to me obtaining a scholarship to attend Texas A&M and to major in agriculture.
How much was that scholarship?
It was the grand total of $1,000, and it paid like $125 a semester, which was starting off about a third of what it cost me to go to school each semester.

So with that scholarship and what I saved from my working in animal projects and things of this nature, I was able to go all the way through UNM without ever having to borrow any money until my last semester, my second year.
Describe how you came and what you brought when you came to enroll the first time.
How did you get here and what did you bring and who brought you?
Well, after I won my scholarship, I had to come and
go through the summer pre-enrollment process.
And at that particular point in time, there was so much going on at home on the farm and stuff that the family just could not come with me.
And so I had to come on my own.
And they took me to Tyler, and I caught the Greyhound bus at Tyler.
And I rode that bus darn near all day long
until it finally dropped me off at the East Gate of the campus.
This would be September or August?
No, this would be like in July.
Of what year?
This was the pre-enrollment deal where you'd come down and sign up for whatever courses you're going to take and all that good stuff.
The same thing kids do now, but I don't think it's changed that much.
But anyway, I came down for that.
It was interesting.
Riding that bus, you kind of become familiar with those who were on that bus with you between the stops.
I eventually found that there were two other kids.
One was a guy named George Strong who was coming in from
A little town up above with Amarillo.
It's the last little town, basically, if you get to before you get to New Mexico.
Dumas.
Dumas.
From Dumas and a guy named Skip.
Gosh, Skip's name.
From Dallas.
And we stopped in Bremont, Texas.
It was one of the stops.
And there was... And this reminded me of the...
Little paintings you see from Saturday Evening Post covers, you know.

Here was this little farming family in their little pickup truck with all their kids and mom and dad are there and here's his son waiting and the bus pulls up and he hugs his mom and shakes his dad's hand and he gets on and all he had was, he didn't have a suitcase, I had a little bag.
He had a brown paper sack that he had his stuff in and...
He was going to Texas A&M because he graduated from Bremont High School's salutatorians.
So he had a scholarship to go to a state-supported institution.
So he was coming down to become a mechanical engineer.
I don't think he ever had trigonometry, physics, calculus, or any of those things that you would need.
But all of us, the four of us, got off that bus.
And I remember right there as we were going down to the systems building, we walked.
from there over to the other side of the campus where they put us in the dorms.
And I remember the systems building being so imposing at the end of that street.
And we thought, golly, boys, we're here.
This is the big town.
And three of us were basically country boys.
One was city boy.
But all of us were basically the same background from working families.
And we all had received a scholarship of some form or fashion to attend it.
And we all ended up being on the work-study program, which was provided by the university to help kids who needed to have a little financial assistance.
And I know that Deward and Skip, I don't know what they ended up doing, but John Turlock, the boy from Bremont and I, in the wedding tables of Duncan Knight on our freshman year.
And all four graduated.
John got his mechanical engineering degree and was a successful engineer.
I kind of lost touch with Dewitt and Skip, but everybody graduating I think went on to other things.
But that was my first experience and that's what I brought with me was that.
And I basically just, if someone back in those days they thought of the typical, I guess I was, small town country boy kind of environment.
a lot of what you found on campus.
Describe the campus physically.
What buildings were where?
What did the campus seem like then?
Oh, it seemed huge to me.
But it really wasn't.
There were about 8,500 students that were enrolled in 1965.
It was the first year that the Corps was non-compulsory.
It was also the first year that
The university was open to admission to women.
But the university itself had not changed very, very much at all.
We did have the MSC.
There was not the Rudder Tower or any of that other stuff.
It was Guy Hall.
The building was there.
And we didn't have, all we had was
the old library.
We didn't have the new one.
Didn't have so many of the buildings that are there on campus that people are so familiar with.
There are a lot more open spaces on campus than there are now.
But it still was to my view a huge place and I was apprehensive to say the least.
How describe life as a fish when you were a freshman?
You know, when I came in, I didn't know much about all this stuff.
I had a scholarship, and I was going to A&M.
And I knew there was this thing called a COR.
All I knew about it was spelled funny.
And I thought it should be C-O-R-E instead of C-O-R-P.
I thought that was CORP, not COR.
That's how ignorant I was.
And when we're going through this registration deal,
had you in these lines, and you don't know why you're in the line, but you get to the front of the line.
And the guy asked me, Army or Air Force?
And I remember being so intimidated and everything else, but I did have enough sense at least to ask one question.
I said, well, what's the difference?
He said, well, to graduate in the Air Force, it's a five-year commitment.
If it's the Army, it's a two-year commitment.
I said, put me in the Army.
So that's how I ended up in the Army ROTC part of it.
They asked me about, which I had a preference about outfit, and I didn't really know what they were talking about there.
And I said, what difference does that make?
Well, there's some dorms over on this side, they're air conditioned.
Others over here on the other side.
And I said, what's the difference in cost?
And they said, well, air conditioned dorms will bring the cost of this and run air conditioned to this.
I said, well, put me in the un-air conditioned ones.
And so that's how I ended up in the outfit that I was in, in the Duncan area.
At that point in time, the Corps was in both the Duncan area and Sevesa.
And I lived in dorm one on the fourth stoop.
So then I got to get to know and meet every upperclassmen there was on all four floors.
What I didn't realize then was being a waiter in the mess hall was like being in another outfit and having to get to meet and know all those pertinent things about the upperclassmen waiters.
as well as all the upperclassmen on the tables that I served.
So it was a real introduction to Corps life very quickly for me.
I do know that when we came down, I went to fish camp.
And they came down to, folks did, to drop me off.
Like I said, I was 18 years old, first time I'd been away from Northeast Texas for very much my whole lifetime.
And I remember going in the dorm, and this is after fish camp.
They brought me my stuff and everything.
I go in there, and there's just two upperclassmen.
One was introduced as my first sergeant, and there was another junior that was with him.
They visited my folks, and they told my folks that they'd had some of the same courses that I had, and they could help me with my studies.
And I remember remarking that it was nice that I made a friend the first day.
campus, and I thought, yeah, it is.
They leave, and I have a little lump in my throat, and I drive off into the quad there, going back home.
I know I'm on my own, all alone.
I go back in that dorm, and I see these two upper classmen.
I said, hey, Terry, Rick.
I said, Terry, Rick, hey, Maggie, we don't know you.
Get out of here and whip out.
I had no idea what they were talking about, but I knew that they were not as friendly as they were before.
And that just went straight downhill for me.
And I know that I finally got in my room, and I said I was going to stay there for a while.
And I do recall later on that day that there was another kid came with his grandmother.
And pretty much the same thing happened as soon as grandmother left.
The treatment started for him, too.
And I remember him running out of the dorm, hollering, grandmother, wait.
Grandmother, wait.
That was the last we saw of him.
So there were 56 freshmen in my outfit.
that we started with and there were 13 of us that graduated.
What the Corps didn't get, grades did.
We did not have the, I don't think we had the restrictions on admissions that we do now.
And so part of the weeding out process took place in school.
And I do recall that
standing on the wall that first week, not wanting any sort of shaved head people sitting next to me very well at all.
And the COC looked to your left and looked to your right at the end of the semester, those guys are not going to be here.
And I thought, well, that was me too.
And sure enough, out of 56, we were down to about 20 some odd after the first semester, 30 some odd, 20 some odd after the second semester.
And 13, like I said, he graduated.
But the thing that I did learn was I learned so much about myself and my ability to deal with persons and situations.
And I learned to assess my fellow man on a different basis than I ever had before.
One thing that it certainly did was it made you all equal.
We're taught we're equal in the eyes of the Lord, but in society, you're not.
You're judged by lots of other factors.
And there, I was taught you're judged on two things, and that is your ability and the content of your character.
And that taught me a lot about myself and my felony.
And I've tried to, I've used those things that I was taught there.
more than just about anything else I ever had in my life.
Describe, particularly during your freshman year, but any other years, events that an outsider might have called hazing.
What were some of the traditions, routines?
Well, most everything that outsiders would call hazing, most everything we did would be called hazing.
I know that there were some physical things that went on,
That certainly get people voted out now.
Would have been too, but it wasn't pervasive.
There was some swatting on the backside from time to time.
Who did that?
Upper classmen.
But I've never had anybody do anything like that to me.
But they did it because they wanted to.
abused me, hurt me, or anything else.
They did it.
It was basically one of these little rituals, I guess you'd say, of passage, so to speak.
When they did those kind of things, it meant that you had passed and mustered, you were accepted, you were approved, you were liked, you were respected type of thing.
And I was never known with meanness or anything else.
If it had, I wouldn't have stood for it.
But I still didn't think it was appropriate.
And I will just tell you that
that all of those things happened to me.
And I never did those things when I was on the president.
I never beat anybody with a broom or an axe hammer or any of that stuff.
I just, I might have physically grabbed somebody's eyes, I say, you know, make them do a lot of exercises and stuff like that.
What were those, just tell them about those.
Oh, well, you, one thing I will say is you had to be physically fit to survive part of this too.
If you were
If you were a flabby fat boy, you were in trouble.
Of course, I came in here being a foreign boy.
I'd been in athletics in high school and all those kind of things.
That was OK for me.
It was no problem at all.
Boys that came in that were not in good shape did suffer as a result of that.
Oh, it was physically demanding.
You had to do push-ups, and you had to do other things.
type of things that were strenuous exercises, stuff that you would see on a football field, but would all be a short duration, would last a little longer sometimes.
I know that it was one of those things too that you got punished as a class quite often.
If some of your classmates weren't doing as they should, you would end up all having to go through certain physical activities

And it eventually got to the point where you, if these people persisted in that, and it was apparent that they just didn't care about their fellow fish, that we had a couple meetings with some of those guys.
And I do recall one guy that, he was from Chicago and was kind of rude and obnoxious.
And we got down to the point where we went to him and said, we're going to pack your bags and we're going to send you back home because you're not having it.
You're hurting.
And I do recall that person, I think for the first time, realizing his life.
But his actions did affect other folks, and he had a responsibility to others.
And he actually said, please, guys, let me just stay.
I'll change.
And he's the one of the 13 that graduated.
Hey, good, good.
So.
Fish Old Lady, was that an important person in your life?
It was a very important person, but it didn't help in my case.
I know that my Fish Old Lady I found was a fish camper friend of mine that I met in a state 4-H leadership conference before and maybe some other function out of high school.
I thought he was going to be my roommate.
I saw this.
It was just wonderful.
I know this person.
His father had attended Texas A&M.
He knew all these things.
He knew how to whip out and all.
And I didn't know what he was talking about.
I had no clue.
I was totally clueless.
And I thought, boy, it's great that I found someone that I know that has his background.
He's going to be really helpful.
We get here, and he just totally spazzes out.
He is frightened to death.
He will not go out.
I have to go out in the hall first because he can't remember the names, and I have to speak to everybody he had followed what I said.
He would never leave his room.
I mean, it was horrible.
He would get up at like 4 in the morning and take his books and hide them in bushes around buildings off the quad so he wouldn't have to come back in the morning to chat.
And I had to clean up the room by myself and all that kind of stuff.
He could not wait until the first semester was over with until he could leave.
And he got a point.
I was thinking, please, I'd be glad if you came.
And he did leave.
He went to the University of Texas.
And someone told me not too long ago that he operates a bicycle repair shop there on the strip.
He's got hair down to his waist.
And he's the perpetual hippie over there, a 50-some-odd-year-old hippie now.
But that's where he ended up.
I ended up then, second semester.
As a matter of fact, they would not let you
After the first two weeks, you didn't get out of the Corps by then.
They would not let you out until the end of the first semester.
And so, as soon as that was over, he was gone.
Then I had a, I ran with another guy.
He was a good guy.
He was from North Texas at Iowa Park, north of Wichita Falls.
And he was an ag engineering major.
He ended up with his Ph.D. here at A&M.

and good guy and he was my roommate for that second semester my fish year and second semester my first semester my sophomore year and he ended getting married and i had another roommate in the outfit for the second semester then i went on staff my junior senior year and had different roommates there too but after that first semester i had wonderful roommates i mean guys i truly cherish uh
You described chow hall routine.
Since you were a waiter, you didn't eat with your outfit.
Tell me about the life of a waiter.
I did the second semester.
Because, Dr. Moreau, what I realized was I was missing out with some of those opportunities for my fish buddies in my outfit because I missed the formations and stuff because I had to go down.
Now, of course, I was going through the stuff in the mess hall that they were going through there,

they didn't know that and I wasn't getting to know those guys like I'd like to and so I was able to give me another job on campus that allowed me a little more flexibility and I could work more hours in every time I had a couple hour break I could go to work you know and so I was able to earn more than waiting tables in the mess hall so that was the first thing
Second semester, I did a little.
Describe mess hall.
Oh, it was.
Routines, traditions, games.
Oh, basically, the mess hall was not a place where you got to languish and eat at your heart's content.
It was an area of constant harassment and consternation to all the freshmen.
I know I said at the table there were three freshmen.
And they had two seniors, a junior, two sophomores, and three freshmen.
Two of us ran hot corner, which is where they deliver the food, the corner end of the table.
And we passed everything down.
And then one guy was giving meal service to the senior.
And then I would give meal service to the junior who was next to me, who ended up being president of his class and the whole bit.
And he was on the association board and everything.
But anyway.
It was, it was, you could never eat small bites in front of your chair.
So you never got to eat very much.
But we got around those circumstances, situations.
And I never recall that one of the sophomores on the table was this guy from, the way I'll text his name is Ernesto J. Pena III.
Blonde hair and blue eyes.
And he would, his favorite thing was making me
which were the peppers.
If you smiled, he'd do something to make you smile.
He'd say, oh, Fish, I can't eat some buzzberries and stuff.
I'd eat those buzzberries, but it didn't bother me too much.
But at our table, we had the three freshmen.
We had some real line-up for class.
They assigned us a certain task.
One of the freshmen, his father was commander of the Special Forces in Vietnam at the time.
And so he had to give a report on the war and things of this nature.
The other guy, he had to give a report on other national affairs and things of this nature.
And mine was unusual rapes, deaths, and murders.
And so we'd get through at the mill, and they'd say, OK, it's report time.
And other upperclassmen would move their chairs around, and we'd go through the reports.
And they'd say, ah, Youngkin, it's your turn.
And I'd go through.

some 80-some-odd-year-old grandmother in Italy that died after she tried to dive off of a patio to get down to another patio and catch it so she could get in the children who were locked in their apartment or whatever.
And some bizarre things.
You know, they say, oh, you're lying, you're lying.
Oh, no, sir.
And I pulled out the article that I'd gone over the library.
You found these things in the San Antonio Light and the San Antonio News Express for some reason.
One of these really warped stories.
So, but that happened on a nightly basis.
And as soon as the upperclassmen would leave, one of my good friends would always say, hey guys, junior privileges.
And we'd start eating like that.
And the upperclassmen would pretty much go at that point.
And so another upperclassman came up and said, we've got junior privileges.
So we'd eat.
What were the nicknames for the food items?
Oh, you had all of them.
You couldn't call anything by its regular name.
And I still recall every one of those things.
salt, pepper, and sand in.
All meat, no matter what it was, was bull neck.
Bread was deal.
You know, if you deal out the loaves of bread like you would cards.
Water was sky.
Butter was grease.
It was everything.
Tea?
Tea was, I don't know, what the heck was tea?
Dessert?
Dessert was cush.
Dang, what was it?
But anyway, beans was artillery.
It was all kinds of things for all the foods.
I had to dine for it.
And a lot of the things that went on at the Mesa were also kind of those memories that you keep.
They'd make you do things to the other upperclassmen, like set their bibs on fire.

When you saw people at a table and they were up there eating, all of a sudden you just kind of see them pooch back in their seats, meant there was some freshman crawling under the table to get to the silver classmate at the end of the table, and they would light his paper napkin he had in his lap, and all of a sudden he'd flame, he'd jump up and start fanning and beating himself.
But the worst thing that happened to me, and of course I did to folks when I was a freshman, was they'd tell you that as a freshman to grease somebody so you'd have these big pats of butter
And they'd have you take these pads and put them in your hand until they got real soft.
Then you'd go up behind the upperclassmen that you're supposed to grease, and you'd go and slap this over his ears, which put the butter into his ear.
And the only way you'd get out is you'd take a nap, and you'd just screw it around in your ear, and you'd finally got out enough where you could go get water in there to shower it out.
But it was terrible.
It was funny, too.
Let's see.
Your outfit?
I was in Company B2.
Booze and D, which has recently been disbanded.
What was the nickname?
Booze and D. Some of the kids came about a year ago or not a year ago, about three or four years ago, and said, Mr. Jenkins, you know, they want us to change our outfit sign.
They want to take the stars and bars off our sign.
Apparently, the Confederate stars and bars were on the outfit sign.
I never realized that.
And I told them, I said, well, I wouldn't worry about that.
I'd worry about them wanting to change your name.
They said, why is that?
I said, it's my mom.
I hated that name.
I said, what are y'all just sitting around and drinking all the time?
I said, no, Mom, we don't.
But anyway, she hated that name.
